{"parse":{"title":"town","pageid":33544,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Town}}\n==English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|tahn|tawn||Bermuda}}\n* {{alter|en|toon||Northumbrian}}\n* {{alter|en|toune|towne||obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|en|:inh|enm:toun|tree=1|text=++}}\n\nCognate with {{cog|stq|Tuun|t=garden}}, {{cog|fy|tún|t=enclosure, garden}}, {{cog|nl|tuin|t=garden}}, {{cog|nds-de|Tuun|t=fence}}, {{cog|de|Zaun|t=fence}}, {{cog|da|-}}, {{cog|sv|-}} and {{cog|no|tun|t=yard}}; also archaic {{cog|cy|din|t=hill}}, {{cog|ga|dún|t=fortress}}. {{doublet|en|dun}}. See also {{m|en|-ton}} and {{m|en|tine|t=to enclose}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈtaʊ̯n/|[ˈtʰaʊ̯n]|a=RP,GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-town.ogg|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-town.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-town.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈtæʊ̯n/|[ˈtʰæʊ̯n]|a=Southern US,Midland US,Mid-Atlantic US,NYC,AU,NZ,[[w:Fronting|fronting]]}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈtaːn/|[ˈtʰaːn]|a=Pittsburgh,ZA,[[w:monophthongization|/aʊ̯/-monophthongization]]}}\n* {{IPA|en|/tuːn/|a=Northumbrian}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊn|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|town}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{wp}}\n{{en-noun|~}}\n[[File:Bastrop Texas1.jpg|right|230px]]\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q3957}}A [[settlement]]; an area with [[residential]] [[district]]s, [[shop]]s and amenities, and its own local [[government]]; especially one larger than a [[village]] and smaller than a [[city]], historically enclosed by a [[fence]] or [[wall]]s, with total [[population]]s ranging from several hundred to more than a [[hundred thousand]] (as of the early 21st century)\n#: {{ux|en|This '''town''' is really dangerous because these youngsters have Beretta handguns.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1920| title=Transactions and Proceedings for the Year |author=Birmingham Archaeological Society | page=142| passage=Apparently the first reference to the making of the '''town''' walls of Stafford (it appears pretty clear that the '''town''' was never surrounded by one continuous wall or stockade, but partly by one and partly by the other) occurs in the Patent Rolls, from which we find that in 1225 permission was granted by the king to the \"good men of Stafford” to collect customs or tolls for a period to enable them to enclose the '''town'''. }}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2001| title=Town and Country in Europe, 1300-1800 |editor=S. R. Epstein |chapter=Town and country in France , 1550–1750 |author=Thomas Brennan | page=250| passage=Walls separated '''town''' and country through much of the early modern period. Walls not only protected '''towns''', they also helped give them a sense of autonomy and identity.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011| title=Slovakia in History |author=Mikuláš Teich; Dušan Kováč; Martin D. Brown | page=42| passage=Fortifications and '''town''' walls clearly highlight the central military significance of '''towns'''. }}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-05-10|author=Audrey Garric\n|volume=188|issue=22|page=30|magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly\n|title= Urban canopies let nature bloom\n|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/may/04/paris-green-roofs-building-climate-environment\n|passage=As '''towns''' continue to grow, replanting vegetation has become a form of urban utopia and green roofs are spreading fast. Last year 1m square metres of plant-covered roofing was built in France, as much as in the US, and 10 times more than in Germany, the pioneer in this field. In Paris 22 hectares of roof have been planted, out of a potential total of 80 hectares.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2014| title=An Economic History of Medieval Europe |author=Norman John Greville Pounds | page=228| passage=The medieval '''town''', at least in continental Europe, was walled, and without its defences it was no '''town'''.}}\n# Any more urbanized centre than the place of reference.\n#: {{ux|en|I'll be in Yonkers, then I'm driving into '''town''' to see the Knicks at the Garden tonight.}}\n#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=4|passage=Judge Short had gone to '''town''', and Farrar was off for a three days' cruise up the lake. I was bitterly regretting I had not gone with him when the distant notes of a coach horn reached my ear, and I descried a four-in-hand winding its way up the inn road from the direction of Mohair.}}\n# {{lb|en|UK|historical}} A rural settlement in which a [[market]] was held at least once a week.\n# The [[resident]]s (as opposed to {{m|en|gown}}: the [[student]]s, faculty, etc.) of a community which is the site of a [[university]].\n# {{lb|en|colloquial|used without an article}} {{non-gloss|Used to refer to a town or similar entity under discussion}}.\n#: {{ux|en|Call me when you get to '''town'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|They put up \"lost dog\" posters all over '''town'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|My apartment is five minutes from the center of '''town'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It's quiet in this part of '''town'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=2|passage=I had occasion{{...}}to make a somewhat long business trip to Chicago, and on my return{{...}}I found Farrar awaiting me in the railway station. He smiled his wonted fraction by way of greeting{{...}}, and finally leading me to his buggy, turned and drove out of '''town'''.}}\n# A [[major]] [[city]], especially one where the speaker is located.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2014|author=Megan R. Wilson|quotee=Scott Talbott|title=15 places in DC where lobbyists talk turkey|journal=The Hill|url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/225491-fifteen-places-in-dc-where-lobbyists-talk-turkey|text=There's always a business theme, even underlying happy hours. You're never off the clock in this '''town'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal|real estate}} A [[townhouse#Noun|townhouse]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Garth Turner|title=The Little Book of Real Estate Wisdom|location=Toronto, O.N.|publisher=w:Key Porter Books|year=2002|page=38|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/littlebookofreal0000turn/page/38/mode/1up|isbn=1-552-63518-X|passage=Detached houses always sell faster than '''towns''' or semis.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Derek Raymaker|title=Suburbs add semi-detached to the mix|work=w:The Globe and Mail|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20230526003623/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/real-estate/suburbs-add-semi-detached-to-the-mix/article18266862/|location=Toronto, O.N.|publisher=w:The Woodbridge Company|date=11 June 2004|issn=0319-0714|oclc=6155622|passage=It's not just market forces that are bringing out the semis and '''towns'''. Municipalities are requiring developers to build a mix of homes into their new planned communities, partly out of a concession to make more efficient use of virgin land, but also to address the need for more affordable housing for families who might not be able to crack a $300,000 mortgage.}}\n# {{lb|en|legal}} A municipal organization, such as a corporation, defined by the laws of the entity of which it is a part.\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} An [[enclosure]] which surrounded the mere [[homestead]] or [[dwelling]] of the [[lord]] of the [[manor]]; by extension, the whole of the land which constituted the [[domain]].\n# {{lb|en|UK|Scotland|dialect|obsolete}} A [[farm]] or [[farmstead]]; also, a [[court]] or [[farmyard]].\n\n====Usage notes====\n* A city is typically larger than a town, which in turn is typically larger than a village. In rural areas, a ''town'' may be considered urban. In urban areas, a ''town'' can be considered suburban; a village in the suburbs. The distinctions are fluid and dependent on subjective perception.\n\n====Hypernyms====\n* {{l|en|settlement}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{lookfrom|en|town}}\n{{col|en|title=Nouns|agrotown\n|assize town\n|bad part of town\n|bedroom town\n|big end of town\n|blow town|no brown in town\n|book town|Campbell Town|Elizabeth Town|Pitt Town|Pitt Town Bottoms|Violet Town\n|boom town,boomtown\n|B-town\n|bytown\n|cathedral town\n|churchtown| O-town\n|clone town\n|closed town\n|coal town\n|college town\n|come upon the town\n|commuter town\n|company town\n|county town\n|cowtown,cow town\n|cross town,cross-town,crosstown\n|cybertown\n|darktown\n|dog town\n|dormitory town\n|down-town,downtown|townselike\n|ecotown\n|fortified town\n|garrison town\n|gentleman about town\n|get out of town\n|ghost town\n|go-to-town,go to town\n|go to town on\n|gray town\n|hat town\n|hill town,hilltown\n|hog town\n|hometown,home town\n|intertown\n|intown\n|in-town\n|in town\n|jerkwater town\n|kirk-town\n|kirktown\n|leave town\n|man-about-town,man about town\n|market town\n|midtown\n|mining town\n|model town\n|monotown\n|multitown\n|new kid in town\n|new town\n|old town\n|oldtown\n|one-camel town|one-blink town\n|one-horse town\n|only game in town\n|on the town|Flo-Town|Tiger Town\n|out-of-town,out of town\n|paint the town\n|paint the town red\n|panchayat town\n|paper town\n|park the beef bus in tuna town\n|post town\n|pound town\n|P-town\n|Radio Town\n|resort town\n|run out of town\n|satellite town\n|shacktown\n|shantytown\n|shanty town\n|shire town\n|skip town\n|small-town\n|smalltown\n|small town\n|spa town\n|stannary town\n|sundowner town\n|sundown town\n|sunset town\n|take someone to brown town\n|take to pound town\n|talk of the town\n|tank town\n|there is a new sheriff in town\n|toast of the town\n|top end of town\n|town and gown\n|town-and-gown\n|townball\n|town ball\n|town belt\n|town bicycle\n|town bike\n|town-building game\n|town camp\n|town car\n|town center,town centre\n|town-clerk\n|town clerk\n|town council\n|town councillor\n|town cress\n|town crier\n|Town Crow\n|town drunk\n|town-dweller\n|town dweller\n|towndweller\n|towned\n|townee\n|towner\n|townfield\n|townfolk\n|townful\n|town gas\n|town hall,townhall\n|townhome\n|townhood\n|town house,townhouse\n|townie\n|townish\n|townland\n|townless\n|townlet\n|townlike\n|townling\n|townly\n|town mail\n|townman\n|town manager\n|townmate\n|town mayor\n|town meeting\n|town planner\n|town planning\n|townscape\n|townsfellow\n|townsfolk\n